================================
 FILE & DIRECTORY COMMANDS
================================

ls  
→ Lists files in a directory.  
Example: ls /var/log

ls -l  
→ Shows detailed file info.  
Example: ls -l /etc

ls -a  
→ Shows hidden files.  
Example: ls -a ~

pwd  
→ Prints current directory.  
Example: pwd

cd /path  
→ Changes directory.  
Example: cd /etc/nginx

cd ..  
→ Moves one level up.  
Example: cd ..

mkdir folder  
→ Creates a new folder.  
Example: mkdir backups

mkdir -p a/b/c  
→ Creates nested folders.  
Example: mkdir -p /opt/app/logs

rm file  
→ Deletes a file.  
Example: rm notes.txt

rm -r folder  
→ Deletes a folder recursively.  
Example: rm -r test_folder

cp file1 file2  
→ Copies a file.  
Example: cp app.conf app_backup.conf

cp -r dir1 dir2  
→ Copies a whole directory.  
Example: cp -r /var/www /backup/

mv old new  
→ Moves or renames files.  
Example: mv file.txt file_old.txt

touch file.txt  
→ Creates an empty file.  
Example: touch server.log

cat file.txt  
→ Displays full file content.  
Example: cat /etc/os-release

head file.txt  
→ Shows first 10 lines.  
Example: head /var/log/syslog

tail file.txt  
→ Shows last 10 lines.  
Example: tail /var/log/auth.log

tail -f file.txt  
→ Shows live logs.  
Example: tail -f /var/log/nginx/access.log


================================
 PERMISSIONS & OWNERSHIP
================================

chmod 755 file  
→ Sets read/write/execute for owner; read/execute for others.  
Example: chmod 755 deploy.sh

chmod u+x file  
→ Adds execute permission for user.  
Example: chmod u+x script.sh

chown user file  
→ Changes file owner.  
Example: chown arnav app.log

chown user:group file  
→ Changes owner and group.  
Example: chown arnav:dev app.log

umask  
→ Shows default permission mask.  
Example: umask

stat file  
→ Shows full file metadata.  
Example: stat index.html


================================
 SEARCHING & FINDING
================================

find /path -name "*.txt"  
→ Finds files by name.  
Example: find /var/log -name "*.log"

find . -type f  
→ Lists only files.  
Example: find . -type f

find . -size +10M  
→ Finds files larger than 10MB.  
Example: find /var -size +100M

grep "text" file  
→ Searches text in file.  
Example: grep "error" app.log

grep -r text folder  
→ Recursive text search.  
Example: grep -r "failed" /etc

locate filename  
→ Quickly finds file by name.  
Example: locate nginx.conf


================================
 NETWORKING COMMANDS
================================

ip a  
→ Shows system IP addresses.  
Example: ip a | grep inet

ip r  
→ Shows routing table.  
Example: ip r

ping google.com  
→ Tests internet connectivity.  
Example: ping -c 4 google.com

curl URL  
→ Fetches content from a URL.  
Example: curl https://api.github.com

curl -I URL  
→ Fetches HTTP headers only.  
Example: curl -I https://google.com

wget URL  
→ Downloads a file.  
Example: wget https://site.com/file.zip

ss -tulpn  
→ Lists open ports & services.  
Example: ss -tulpn | grep 80

nslookup domain  
→ DNS query lookup.  
Example: nslookup google.com

dig domain  
→ Advanced DNS lookup.  
Example: dig google.com +short

ssh user@host  
→ Connects to SSH server.  
Example: ssh ubuntu@192.168.1.10

scp file user@host:/path  
→ Copies file to remote server.  
Example: scp backup.zip root@10.0.0.5:/tmp/


================================
 PROCESS MANAGEMENT
================================

ps  
→ Shows your running processes.  
Example: ps

ps aux  
→ Shows all system processes.  
Example: ps aux | grep nginx

top  
→ Live process and CPU monitor.  
Example: top

htop  
→ Improved top (if installed).  
Example: htop

kill PID  
→ Stops a process.  
Example: kill 1234

kill -9 PID  
→ Force kills a process.  
Example: kill -9 1234

pkill name  
→ Kills process by name.  
Example: pkill nginx

nice -n 10 command  
→ Runs command with low priority.  
Example: nice -n 10 backup.sh

renice PID  
→ Changes priority of running process.  
Example: renice 5 1234


================================
 DISK & STORAGE COMMANDS
================================

df -h  
→ Shows disk space usage.  
Example: df -h

du -sh folder  
→ Shows folder size.  
Example: du -sh /var/log

lsblk  
→ Lists block devices.  
Example: lsblk

fdisk -l  
→ Lists disk partitions.  
Example: sudo fdisk -l

mount /dev/sdX /mnt  
→ Mounts a device.  
Example: mount /dev/sdb1 /mnt

umount /mnt  
→ Unmounts device.  
Example: umount /mnt


================================
 USER & GROUP MANAGEMENT
================================

whoami  
→ Shows your username.  
Example: whoami

id  
→ Shows user ID and groups.  
Example: id arnav

adduser username  
→ Creates new user.  
Example: adduser admin

passwd username  
→ Sets user password.  
Example: passwd admin

usermod -aG group user  
→ Adds user to group.  
Example: usermod -aG sudo arnav

groups user  
→ Shows user's groups.  
Example: groups arnav


================================
 SERVICES / SYSTEMCTL
================================

systemctl status service  
→ Shows service status.  
Example: systemctl status nginx

systemctl start service  
→ Starts a service.  
Example: systemctl start docker

systemctl stop service  
→ Stops a service.  
Example: systemctl stop apache2

systemctl enable service  
→ Enables auto startup.  
Example: systemctl enable docker

systemctl disable service  
→ Disables auto startup.  
Example: systemctl disable apache2


================================
 PACKAGE MANAGEMENT
================================

apt update  
→ Updates package index.  
Example: sudo apt update

apt upgrade  
→ Installs updates.  
Example: sudo apt upgrade

apt install pkg  
→ Installs a package.  
Example: sudo apt install nginx

yum install pkg  
→ Installs package on RHEL/CentOS.  
Example: sudo yum install httpd


================================
 ENV VARIABLES
================================

echo $VAR  
→ Shows variable value.  
Example: echo $PATH

export VAR=value  
→ Sets environment variable.  
Example: export ENV=prod

unset VAR  
→ Removes variable.  
Example: unset ENV

printenv  
→ Shows environment variables.  
Example: printenv


================================
 COMPRESS / EXTRACT
================================

tar -czvf file.tar.gz folder  
→ Creates compressed tar.  
Example: tar -czvf logs.tar.gz /var/log

tar -xzvf file.tar.gz  
→ Extracts compressed tar.  
Example: tar -xzvf logs.tar.gz

zip file.zip folder  
→ Creates ZIP file.  
Example: zip -r backup.zip /etc

unzip file.zip  
→ Extracts ZIP.  
Example: unzip backup.zip


================================
 SSH & SECURITY
================================

ssh user@host  
→ SSH login.  
Example: ssh root@10.0.0.5

ssh-keygen  
→ Generates SSH keys.  
Example: ssh-keygen -t rsa

ssh-copy-id user@host  
→ Copies public key to server.  
Example: ssh-copy-id ubuntu@10.0.0.5

ufw enable  
→ Enables firewall.  
Example: sudo ufw enable

ufw allow 22  
→ Allows SSH.  
Example: sudo ufw allow 22


================================
 CRON JOBS
================================

crontab -e  
→ Edits cron jobs.  
Example: crontab -e

crontab -l  
→ Lists cron jobs.  
Example: crontab -l


================================
 LOGS & TROUBLESHOOTING
================================

journalctl -u service  
→ Shows logs for a service.  
Example: journalctl -u nginx

journalctl -f  
→ Follows logs in real time.  
Example: journalctl -f

dmesg  
→ Shows kernel/hardware logs.  
Example: dmesg | tail

tail -f /var/log/syslog  
→ Live system logs (Ubuntu).  
Example: tail -f /var/log/syslog

tail -f /var/log/messages  
→ Live logs (CentOS/RHEL).  
Example: tail -f /var/log/messages

